    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down.</placeName>
                    <date>16<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Lubbock</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Very many thanks for your most useful note: I was quite in error about aphis.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I shall be most truly glad to see you on Saturday if you are able to come.— If I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. turn bad in time to let you know, I would send down, but I hope I may not.—</p>
<p>I have stumbled on one of my M.S. reference to paper of L. Dufour, in Annal des Sc. (3<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> series) Tom 3. p. 79, in which he says, (if I have not misunderstood him) that in certain degraded Diptera, the ovarian vesicle assumes the shape “ebauche”, in the ovary, of the <hi rend="underline">pupa</hi>:—(p. 87) “at no time assumes the form of <hi rend="underline">larva</hi>”.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Would you be so <hi rend="doubleUnderline">very kind</hi> as to look at this paper, &amp; give me your opinion when we meet on Saturday.</p>
<p>Yours very truly | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">3.1 of my] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">3.1 M.S.] <hi rend="italic">added</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">3.2 have] <hi rend="italic">over</hi> ‘do’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n4">3.3 degraded] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated by the relationship to the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2433.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Lubbock, 15 March 1859</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD nevertheless remained doubtful about this point: see following letter and n. 5.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The ‘M.S. reference’ was a note CD had written for the chapter in his species book on laws of variation. It is transcribed in an appendix to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection</hi></ref>, pp. 573–4. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2178.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Dufour 1845</ref>, p. 79, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1409.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Léon Jean Marie Dufour</ref> had stated: ‘Je répète donc que les Pupipares … ne produisent pas un véritable oeuf. Du moins la vésicule ovarienne prend dans l’ovaire même les traits ébauchés de la pupe. J’ai donc cru prudent, en parlant du premier produit de la conception, de préférer le nom d’<hi rend="italic">embryon</hi>.’</note>
        </div>        
            
